
The CSS Solution
CSS

/* Container setup */
.yellowFade-card {
  display: grid;
  gap: 1.5rem;
  align-items: center;
}

/* 1. Mobile Layout (Stacking) */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  /* This 'dissolves' the wrapper divs so the h3, h4, p, and img 
     behave as direct siblings in the grid */
  .yellowFade-card > div {
    display: contents;
  }

  .yellowFade-card h3 { order: 1; }
  .yellowFade-card h4 { order: 2; }
  .yellowFade-card img { order: 3; } /* Moves image between h4 and p */
  .yellowFade-card p { order: 4; }
}

/* 2. Desktop Layout (Side-by-Side) */
@media (min-width: 769px) {
  .yellowFade-card {
    grid-template-columns: 1.2fr 0.8fr; /* Text side slightly wider */
  }

  /* Ensures the first div (text) stays left and second (img) stays right */
  .yellowFade-card > div:first-child {
    grid-column: 1;
  }
  
  .yellowFade-card > div:last-child {
    grid-column: 2;
  }

  /* Make sure image fits the column */
  .yellowFade-card img {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    display: block;
  }
}

How this works:

    display: contents: This is the "magic trick." It tells the browser to act as if the <div> wrappers don't exist for layout purposes, but it keeps them in the HTML for styling or accessibility. This allows the order property to work on the individual tags inside.

    The order property: On mobile, we assign a numerical order to each element. Since the image is now a "sibling" of the text elements (thanks to display: contents), we can slide it right into the 3rd slot.

    Desktop Stability: By defining grid-template-columns on desktop, we force the two original wrapper div blocks back into their side-by-side positions.

A Quick Tip for White Center Images

Since you're working with project photography, you might find that the image looks a bit "short" next to that long paragraph on desktop. You can add align-self: start; to the image container in the desktop media query if you want the image to stick to the top of the card rather than centering vertically.

